<DOC><DOCNO> WSJ870501-0006 </DOCNO><HL> Journal Reporters Stewart,Hertzberg Win Loeb Award</HL><DD> 05/01/87</DD><SO> WALL STREET JOURNAL (J)</SO><IN> DJPUBLISHING (PUB) </IN><DATELINE> NEW YORK  </DATELINE><TEXT>   Daniel Hertzberg and James B. Stewart, reporters for The Wall Street Journal, were named winners of a Gerald Loeb award for deadline reporting for their coverage of the Wall Street insider-trading scandal.    Messrs. Hertzberg and Stewart, members of the Journal's New York bureau, specialize in coverage of mergers and acquisitions.    The Loeb awards were established in 1957 by the late Gerald Loeb, who was a vice chairman of E.F. Hutton andamp; Co., to recognize significant contributions to the public understanding of business and financial issues.    The award includes a $1,000 prize. Winners will be honored June 29 at a dinner in New York.    The awards are administered by the John E. Anderson Graduate School of Management at the University of California at Los Angeles. </TEXT></DOC>